{"title_page": "Norbert Bl\u00fcm", "text_new": "{{short description|German federal legislator}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image               = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg\n| imagesize           = 250px\n| office              = [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Minister of Labour and Social Affairs]]\n| term_start          = 4 October 1982\n| term_end            = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor         = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor           = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| nationality         = German\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|23|1935|7|21}}\n| death_place         = [[Bonn]], Germany\n| party               = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Marita Bl\u00fcm (n\u00e9e Binger)|1964}}\n| children            = 3\n| education           = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Bonn]]\n* [[University of Cologne]]\n}}\n| occupation          = \n| signature           = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| chancellor          = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| office2             = Member of the [[Bundestag]]<br>for [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n| termstart2          = 1972\n| termend2            = 1981\n| office3             = Member of the [[Bundestag]]<br>for [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n| termstart3          = 1983\n| termend3            = 2002\n| awards              = [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]] (2000)<br>[[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] (2001)<br>[[Leopold Kunschak Prize]] (2005)\n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=General Anzeiger |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zeit1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-frueherer-arbeitsminister-im-alter-von-84-jahren-gestorben-a-74ccbfb1-ce4f-4e06-b3d5-644ec7b31a23 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a German politician who served as a [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] North Rhine-Westphalia (1987\u20131999), and [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Minister of Labour and Social Affairs]]. \n\nBl\u00fcm was the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany. He served as a member of the [[Bundestag]] from 1972 to 1981 and again from 1983 to 2002. Bl\u00fcm was part of the left wing of the conservative [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union (CDU)]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm attended the ''[[Volksschule]]''. In 1950, aged 15, Bl\u00fcm joined the CDU.<ref name=\"Hofmann\">{{cite news|last=Hofmann|first=Gunter|url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/norbert-bluem-sozialpolitiker-cdu-helmut-kohl-minister-nachruf/komplettansicht|title=K\u00e4mpfer f\u00fcr den Sozialstaat|date=24 April 2020|work=[[Die Zeit]]|access-date=24 April 2020|location=Hamburg|language=de}}</ref> He later trained and worked locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]] until 1957. He was engaged in the factory as a youth representative. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts affiliation, the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Norbert+Bl%C3%BCm/0/12207.html |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm - Munzinger Biographie |website=www.munzinger.de |access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> In 1961 he passed his Abitur at a [[night school]] in Mainz, thereby obtaining the university entrance qualification.\n\nHe studied German language and literature, history, philosophy and theology at the [[University of Bonn]] and [[University of Cologne]] until 1967.<ref name=\"Lingen\" /> In 1967, he received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate of philosophy]] (PhD) with the dissertation ''Willenslehre und Soziallehre bei [[Ferdinand T\u00f6nnies]]. Ein Beitrag zum Verst\u00e4ndnis von \"Gemeinschaft und Gesellschaft\"'' in Bonn.<ref name=\"Lingen\">{{cite web |last=Lingen |first=Markus |date=24 April 2020 |title=Geschichte der CDU: Norbert Bl\u00fcm |url=https://www.kas.de/de/web/geschichte-der-cdu/personen/biogramm-detail/-/content/norbert-bluem |work=kas.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung e.V. |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{OCLC|5735776}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1977 to 1987 Bl\u00fcm was chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Employees' Association]].<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He was a member of the CDU federal executive committee from 1969 to 2000. He was chairman of the CDU of the state of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] from 1987 to 1999.\n\nBl\u00fcm was a member of the [[Bundestag]] for the CDU from 1972 to 1981 and from 1983 to 2002.<ref name=\"Hofmann\" /> He was vice chairman of the federal CDU from 1981 to 1990 and again from 1992 to 2000.<ref name=\"Lingen\" />\n\nBl\u00fcm was [[Federal Minister for Labour and Social Affairs (Germany)|Federal Minister for Labour and Social Affairs ]] from 1982 to 1998.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> As minister, he was responsible for reforms and changes in the pension system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben: K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp|last=tagesschau.de|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=tagesschau.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> His greatest political success was the introduction of [[Long-term care insurance in Germany|long-term care insurance]] (''Pflegeversicherung'') in 1995,<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /><ref name=\"Hofmann\" /> after those reform plans were hotly and controversially debated in the Bundestag.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sanders |first=Katrin |date=21 April 2019 |title=Die Gefahr, durch Pflege arm zu werden |url=https://www.deutschlandfunk.de/einfuehrung-der-pflegeversicherung-die-gefahr-durch-pflege.724.de.html?dram:article_id=446861 |work=deutschlandfunk.de |location=Cologne |publisher=Deutschlandradio |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nBl\u00fcm adhered to Christian values and belonged to the left wing of the generally centre-right CDU.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cordes-Strehle |first=Antraud |date=24 April 2020 |title=K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Cologne |publisher=Westdeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> During his time in office, Bl\u00fcm held out and pushed back against demands by fellow CDU politicians to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA popular quotation attributed to him is \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated as: \"Pensions are safe\"), based on the governmental slogan he wielded in 1986: \"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\" (\"One thing is safe: pensions\").<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /> This quotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference that would be used by his opponents and critics for years to come.<ref name=\"Hofmann\" />\n\nThe politician was a fervent supporter of human rights. On a trip to Chile in 1987, he accused former dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]] of torture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/nachrichten/bluem-nachruf-100.html|title=Der ehrliche Arbeiter: Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist tot|last=WDR|date=2020-04-24|website=www1.wdr.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm once said that \"politics is a struggle\". \"Whoever is in search of harmony must look for another profession. (...) But if you want to change something, you cannot please everybody.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.upday.com/de/norbert-bluem-die-sichere-rente-bleibt-in-erinnerung/|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm: Die 'sichere Rente' bleibt in Erinnerung|date=2020-04-24|website=upday News DE|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n[[File:KAS-Bl\u00fcm, Norbert-Bild-6629-1.jpg|alt=Bl\u00fcm giving a speech|thumb|Bl\u00fcm (1990) giving a speech in the state election campaign of North Rhine-Westphalia]]\nCore issues of his politics were [[social justice]] and the fight against [[unemployment]]. For Bl\u00fcm, \"the little people\" were important, which is why he tried to prevent a division of society into rich and poor with his politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben: K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp|last=tagesschau.de|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=tagesschau.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He saw social peace threatened by the [[Agenda 2010]] that was later passed by the German government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freitag.de/autoren/michael-jaeger/so-wuenscht-man-sich-politiker|title=Nachruf - So w\u00fcnscht man sich Politiker|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=www.freitag.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vehlewald |first1=Hans-J\u00f6rg |last2=Koelbl |first2=Susanne |date=27 November 1995 |title='Das ist Psychokrieg' |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9236202.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=21 October 1996 |title=Anw\u00fcrfe aus \u00dcbersee |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9107899.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite his good relationship with Helmut Kohl, Bl\u00fcm criticized his handling of the [[CDU donations scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.n-tv.de/politik/Kohls-streitbarer-Herz-Jesu-Mann-article21737429.html|title=Kohls streitbarer Herz-Jesu-Mann|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=n-tv.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter his departure from the Bundestag in 2002, he continued to comment on political issues publicly. Because of his criticism of [[Israel|Israel]] in the [[List of modern conflicts in the Middle East|Middle East conflict]], he was sometimes accused of [[antisemitism]], which he rejected.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-rente-1.4887213|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm - Rummelboxer der Politik|work=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|language=de|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/politik/bluem-wehrt-sich-gegen-antisemitismus-vorwuerfe_aid-8495567|title='Bin ein Freund Israels': Bl\u00fcm wehrt sich gegen Antisemitismus-Vorw\u00fcrfe|last=|first=|date=21 June 2002|website=RP ONLINE|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he criticised the CDU's refugee policy because of the cold-hearted discussion about refugees. During the refugee crisis, the former minister visited the Greek refugee camp [[Idomeni]] in 2016 and heavily criticized the EU's treatment of refugees (\"This kind of brutality is unworthy of European culture\"). Out of solidarity he slept one night in the [[refugee camp]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/griechenland-norbert-bluem-uebernachtet-in-idomeni-a-1081999-amp.html|title=Griechenland: Norbert Bl\u00fcm \u00fcbernachtet in Idomeni - DER SPIEGEL|last=|first=|date=12 March 2016|website=www.spiegel.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he opposed an unconditional [[basic income]], on which [[Switzerland]] held a [[referendum]] at this time. It would be \"unfair\" and an \"attempted escape from welfare state responsibility\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/soziales/schweiz-warum-wir-das-grundeinkommen-fuer-k-eine-gute-idee-halten-a-1095572.html|title=Schweiz: Warum wir das Grundeinkommen f\u00fcr (k)eine gute Idee halten|last=Diekmann|first=Florian|date=4 Jun 2016|website=www.spiegel.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBl\u00fcm was married to Marita Bl\u00fcm (n\u00e9e Binger) since 1964.<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /><ref name=\"NDR\" /> The couple had three children, a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"NDR\" />\n\nAfter [[Sepsis|blood poisoning]] in 2019, Bl\u00fcm was paralyzed in his arms and legs.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-nach-blutvergiftung-von-schultern-abwaerts-gelaehmt-a-7c030914-7fdc-4a54-8ffe-10e0491ad061|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm nach Blutvergiftung von Schultern abw\u00e4rts gel\u00e4hmt|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=www.spiegel.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He commented in a guest article for the German weekly ''[[Die Zeit]]'' in March 2020 about his new life in a wheelchair due to his paralysis, in which he compared his position to that of a puppet whose strings were pulled so that its parts dangled incoherently in the air: \"Like a thief in the night, disaster broke into my life in the form of insidious blood poisoning\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeit.de/2020/12/laehmung-behinderung-rollstuhl-lebensqualitaet-krankheit|title=Was bedeutet mein Ungl\u00fcck?|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=www.zeit.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm died in Bonn on 23 April 2020.<ref name=\"NDR\">{{cite web |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/norbert-bluem-109.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Hamburg |publisher=Norddeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* Member of the Advisory Board of the Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member (since 1949)<ref>{{cite news |last=Viering |first=Jonas |date=17 May 2010 |title=\"Bald sind wir wieder bei der Tagel\u00f6hnerei\" (Interview) |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/karriere/norbert-bluem-zum-tag-der-arbeit-bald-sind-wir-wieder-bei-der-tageloehnerei-1.555703 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2000: [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]<ref name=\"Schlamp\">{{cite news |last=Schlamp |first=Hans-J\u00fcrgen |date=24 April 2020 |title=Der Rentenversprecher |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-ein-nachruf-a-44b5f142-83f2-4646-9a2e-8254c9326b27 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2001: [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]]<ref name=\"Schlamp\" />\n* 2005: [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=11 March 2005 |title=Einladung zur Pressekonferenz mit BM a.D. Norbert Bl\u00fcm und Werner Fasslabend |url=https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20050309_OTS0130/einladung-zur-pressekonferenz-mit-bm-ad-norbert-bluem-und-werner-fasslabend |work=ots.at |location=Vienna |publisher=APA-OTS |language=de |agency=APA |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{DNB portal|118722395}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=9 October 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', 9 June 2001\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/cocoon/barch/1121/z/z1960a/kap1_2/para2_124.html Kabinettsprotokolle Online \"Bl\u00fcm, Norbert\"] (in German) bundesarchiv.de\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German federal legislator}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Norbert Bl\u00fcm\n| image               = Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F078539-0037, Wiesbaden, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg\n| imagesize           = 250px\n| office              = [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Minister of Labour and Social Affairs]]\n| term_start          = 4 October 1982\n| term_end            = 27 October 1998\n| predecessor         = [[Heinz Westphal]]\n| successor           = [[Walter Riester]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1935|7|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], [[People's State of Hesse]], [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]\n| nationality         = German\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|df=yes|2020|04|23|1935|7|21}}\n| death_place         = [[Bonn]], Germany\n| party               = [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]\n| spouse              = {{marriage|Marita Bl\u00fcm (n\u00e9e Binger)|1964}}\n| children            = 3\n| education           = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Bonn]]\n* [[University of Cologne]]\n}}\n| occupation          = \n| signature           = \n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| chancellor          = [[Helmut Kohl]]\n| office2             = Member of the [[Bundestag]]<br>for [[Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n| termstart2          = 1972\n| termend2            = 1981\n| office3             = Member of the [[Bundestag]]<br>for [[North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n| termstart3          = 1983\n| termend3            = 2002\n| awards              = [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]] (2000)<br>[[Leipzig Human Rights Award]] (2001)<br>[[Leopold Kunschak Prize]] (2005)\n}}\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F054629-0029, Ludwigshafen, CDU-Bundesparteitag.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm (left) with [[Richard von Weizs\u00e4cker]] in 1978]]\n[[File:Bundesarchiv B 145 Bild-F073616-0021, Mainz, CDU-Bundesparteitag, Bl\u00fcm.jpg|thumb|Norbert Bl\u00fcm in 1986]]\n'''Norbert Bl\u00fcm''' (21 July 1935 \u2013 23 April 2020)<ref>{{cite news |last=L\u00fcke |first=Ulrich |date=24 April 2020 |title=Ein Gro\u00dfer der Bonner Republik |url=https://www.general-anzeiger-bonn.de/news/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-nachruf-auf-einen-grossen-der-bonner-republik_aid-50222203 |work=General Anzeiger |location=Bonn |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Zeit1\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist gestorben |url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/frueherer-arbeitsminister-norbert-bluem-gestorben |work=[[Die Zeit]] |location=Hamburg |agency=dpa |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Fr\u00fcherer Arbeitsminister Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-gestorben-1.4887153 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Spiegel\">{{cite news |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-frueherer-arbeitsminister-im-alter-von-84-jahren-gestorben-a-74ccbfb1-ce4f-4e06-b3d5-644ec7b31a23 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> was a German politician who served as a [[Federation|federal]] [[legislator]] from [[North Rhine-Westphalia]], chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|CDU]] North Rhine-Westphalia (1987\u20131999), and [[Federal Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs|Minister of Labour and Social Affairs]]. \n\nBl\u00fcm was the only cabinet member who served in his function for all sixteen years of [[Helmut Kohl]]'s time as [[prime minister|Chancellor]] of Germany. He served as a member of the [[Bundestag]] from 1972 to 1981 and again from 1983 to 2002. Bl\u00fcm was part of the left wing of the conservative [[Christian Democratic Union of Germany|Christian Democratic Union (CDU)]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[R\u00fcsselsheim]], Bl\u00fcm attended the ''[[Volksschule]]''. In 1950, aged 15, Bl\u00fcm joined the CDU.<ref name=\"Hofmann\">{{cite news|last=Hofmann|first=Gunter|url=https://www.zeit.de/politik/deutschland/2020-04/norbert-bluem-sozialpolitiker-cdu-helmut-kohl-minister-nachruf/komplettansicht|title=K\u00e4mpfer f\u00fcr den Sozialstaat|date=24 April 2020|work=[[Die Zeit]]|access-date=24 April 2020|location=Hamburg|language=de}}</ref> He later trained and worked locally as a toolmaker for [[Adam Opel AG|Opel]] until 1957. He was engaged in the factory as a youth representative. During this time, he was a founding member of the local Boy Scouts affiliation, the [[Deutsche Pfadfinderschaft Sankt Georg]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.munzinger.de/search/portrait/Norbert+Bl%C3%BCm/0/12207.html |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm - Munzinger Biographie |website=www.munzinger.de |access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> In 1961 he passed his Abitur at a [[night school]] in Mainz, thereby obtaining the university entrance qualification.\n\nHe studied German language and literature, history, philosophy and theology at the [[University of Bonn]] and [[University of Cologne]] until 1967.<ref name=\"Lingen\" /> In 1967, he received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|doctorate of philosophy]] (PhD) with the dissertation ''Willenslehre und Soziallehre bei Ferdinand T\u00f6nnies. Ein Beitrag zum Verst\u00e4ndnis von \"Gemeinschaft und Gesellschaft\"'' in Bonn.<ref name=\"Lingen\">{{cite web |last=Lingen |first=Markus |date=24 April 2020 |title=Geschichte der CDU: Norbert Bl\u00fcm |url=https://www.kas.de/de/web/geschichte-der-cdu/personen/biogramm-detail/-/content/norbert-bluem |work=kas.de |location=Berlin |publisher=Konrad-Adenauer-Stiftung e.V. |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{OCLC|5735776}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFrom 1977 to 1987 Bl\u00fcm was chairman of the [[Christian Democratic Employees' Association]].<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> He was a member of the CDU federal executive committee from 1969 to 2000. He was chairman of the CDU of the state of [[North Rhine-Westphalia]] from 1987 to 1999.\n\nBl\u00fcm was a member of the [[Bundestag]] for the CDU from 1972 to 1981 and from 1983 to 2002.<ref name=\"Hofmann\" /> He was vice chairman of the federal CDU from 1981 to 1990 and again from 1992 to 2000.<ref name=\"Lingen\" />\n\nBl\u00fcm was [[Federal Minister for Labour and Social Affairs (Germany)|Federal Minister for Labour and Social Affairs ]] from 1982 to 1998.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /> As minister, he was responsible for reforms and changes in the pension system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben: K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp|last=tagesschau.de|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=tagesschau.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> His greatest political success was the introduction of [[Long-term care insurance in Germany|long-term care insurance]] (''Pflegeversicherung'') in 1995,<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /><ref name=\"Hofmann\" /> after those reform plans were hotly and controversially debated in the Bundestag.<ref>{{cite web |last=Sanders |first=Katrin |date=21 April 2019 |title=Die Gefahr, durch Pflege arm zu werden |url=https://www.deutschlandfunk.de/einfuehrung-der-pflegeversicherung-die-gefahr-durch-pflege.724.de.html?dram:article_id=446861 |work=deutschlandfunk.de |location=Cologne |publisher=Deutschlandradio |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\nBl\u00fcm adhered to Christian values and belonged to the left wing of the generally centre-right CDU.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cordes-Strehle |first=Antraud |date=24 April 2020 |title=K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Cologne |publisher=Westdeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> During his time in office, Bl\u00fcm held out and pushed back against demands by fellow CDU politicians to raise the federal retirement age from 65 to 70.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mitchener |first=Brandon |date=9 November 1992 |title=German Public Spending Cuts Spark Infighting |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/11/09/business/worldbusiness/IHT-german-public-spending-cuts-spark-infighting.html |work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |location=New York City |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nA popular quotation attributed to him is \"Die Rente ist sicher\" (loosely translated as: \"Pensions are safe\"), based on the governmental slogan he wielded in 1986: \"Eins ist sicher: Die Rente\" (\"One thing is safe: pensions\").<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /> This quotation quickly gained notoriety in Germany and became a popular target for [[comedy]], as well as a cynical reference that would be used by his opponents and critics for years to come.<ref name=\"Hofmann\" />\n\nThe politician was a fervent supporter of human rights. On a trip to Chile in 1987, he accused former dictator [[Augusto Pinochet]] of torture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www1.wdr.de/nachrichten/bluem-nachruf-100.html|title=Der ehrliche Arbeiter: Norbert Bl\u00fcm ist tot|last=WDR|date=2020-04-24|website=www1.wdr.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm once said that \"politics is a struggle\". \"Whoever is in search of harmony must look for another profession. (...) But if you want to change something, you cannot please everybody.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.upday.com/de/norbert-bluem-die-sichere-rente-bleibt-in-erinnerung/|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm: Die 'sichere Rente' bleibt in Erinnerung|date=2020-04-24|website=upday News DE|language=de-DE|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n[[File:KAS-Bl\u00fcm, Norbert-Bild-6629-1.jpg|alt=Bl\u00fcm giving a speech|thumb|Bl\u00fcm (1990) giving a speech in the state election campaign of North Rhine-Westphalia]]\nCore issues of his politics were [[social justice]] and the fight against [[unemployment]]. For Bl\u00fcm, \"the little people\" were important, which is why he tried to prevent a division of society into rich and poor with his politics.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/bluemnorbert-nachruf-101.html|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben: K\u00e4mpfer und Kumpeltyp|last=tagesschau.de|first=|date=24 March 2020|website=tagesschau.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He saw social peace threatened by the [[Agenda 2010]] that was later passed by the German government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.freitag.de/autoren/michael-jaeger/so-wuenscht-man-sich-politiker|title=Nachruf - So w\u00fcnscht man sich Politiker|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=www.freitag.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm was an outspoken critic of [[Scientology]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vehlewald |first1=Hans-J\u00f6rg |last2=Koelbl |first2=Susanne |date=27 November 1995 |title='Das ist Psychokrieg' |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9236202.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref> As a consequence, he was targeted by Scientology advocates, who would claim that the organization was a victim of religious [[discrimination]] in Germany.<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=21 October 1996 |title=Anw\u00fcrfe aus \u00dcbersee |url=https://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9107899.html |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDespite his good relationship with Helmut Kohl, Bl\u00fcm criticized his handling of the [[CDU donations scandal]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.n-tv.de/politik/Kohls-streitbarer-Herz-Jesu-Mann-article21737429.html|title=Kohls streitbarer Herz-Jesu-Mann|last=|first=|date=24 April 2020|website=n-tv.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter his departure from the Bundestag in 2002, he continued to comment on political issues publicly. Because of his criticism of [[Israel|Israel]] in the [[List of modern conflicts in the Middle East|Middle East conflict]], he was sometimes accused of [[antisemitism]], which he rejected.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/politik/norbert-bluem-rente-1.4887213|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm - Rummelboxer der Politik|work=S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung|language=de|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rp-online.de/politik/bluem-wehrt-sich-gegen-antisemitismus-vorwuerfe_aid-8495567|title='Bin ein Freund Israels': Bl\u00fcm wehrt sich gegen Antisemitismus-Vorw\u00fcrfe|last=|first=|date=21 June 2002|website=RP ONLINE|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he criticised the CDU's refugee policy because of the cold-hearted discussion about refugees. During the refugee crisis, the former minister visited the Greek refugee camp [[Idomeni]] in 2016 and heavily criticized the EU's treatment of refugees (\"This kind of brutality is unworthy of European culture\"). Out of solidarity he slept one night in the [[refugee camp]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/griechenland-norbert-bluem-uebernachtet-in-idomeni-a-1081999-amp.html|title=Griechenland: Norbert Bl\u00fcm \u00fcbernachtet in Idomeni - DER SPIEGEL|last=|first=|date=12 March 2016|website=www.spiegel.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016 he opposed an unconditional [[basic income]], on which [[Switzerland]] held a [[referendum]] at this time. It would be \"unfair\" and an \"attempted escape from welfare state responsibility\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/soziales/schweiz-warum-wir-das-grundeinkommen-fuer-k-eine-gute-idee-halten-a-1095572.html|title=Schweiz: Warum wir das Grundeinkommen f\u00fcr (k)eine gute Idee halten|last=Diekmann|first=Florian|date=4 Jun 2016|website=www.spiegel.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBl\u00fcm was married to Marita Bl\u00fcm (n\u00e9e Binger) since 1964.<ref name=\"Zeit1\" /><ref name=\"NDR\" /> The couple had three children, a son and two daughters.<ref name=\"NDR\" />\n\nAfter [[Sepsis|blood poisoning]] in 2019, Bl\u00fcm was paralyzed in his arms and legs.<ref name=\"Spiegel\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-nach-blutvergiftung-von-schultern-abwaerts-gelaehmt-a-7c030914-7fdc-4a54-8ffe-10e0491ad061|title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm nach Blutvergiftung von Schultern abw\u00e4rts gel\u00e4hmt|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=www.spiegel.de|language=de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref> He commented in a guest article for the German weekly ''[[Die Zeit]]'' in March 2020 about his new life in a wheelchair due to his paralysis, in which he compared his position to that of a puppet whose strings were pulled so that its parts dangled incoherently in the air: \"Like a thief in the night, disaster broke into my life in the form of insidious blood poisoning\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeit.de/2020/12/laehmung-behinderung-rollstuhl-lebensqualitaet-krankheit|title=Was bedeutet mein Ungl\u00fcck?|last=|first=|date=11 March 2020|website=www.zeit.de|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\nBl\u00fcm died in Bonn on 23 April 2020.<ref name=\"NDR\">{{cite web |last= |first= |date=24 April 2020 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm gestorben |url=https://www.tagesschau.de/inland/norbert-bluem-109.html |work=tagesschau.de |location=Hamburg |publisher=Norddeutscher Rundfunk |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\n* Member of the Advisory Board of the Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize of the City of Cologne<ref>[https://www.stadt-koeln.de/artikel/00045/index.html Hans B\u00f6ckler Prize, Kuratorium] City of Cologne.</ref>\n* Green Helmets, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://gruenhelme.de/team-blank/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] Green Helmets.</ref>\n* [[Bonn Minster]], Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.ksta.de/stiftung-fuer-das-bonner-muenster-13831158 Stiftung f\u00fcr das Bonner M\u00fcnster] [[K\u00f6lner Stadt-Anzeiger]], May 3, 2004.</ref>\n* St. Maria zur Wiese, Member of the Board of Trustees<ref>[https://www.bauhuette-wiesenkirche.de/de/uber-uns/kuratorium/ Board of Trustees] St. Maria zur Wiese.</ref>\n* [[IG Metall]], Member (since 1949)<ref>{{cite news |last=Viering |first=Jonas |date=17 May 2010 |title=\"Bald sind wir wieder bei der Tagel\u00f6hnerei\" (Interview) |url=https://www.sueddeutsche.de/karriere/norbert-bluem-zum-tag-der-arbeit-bald-sind-wir-wieder-bei-der-tageloehnerei-1.555703 |work=[[S\u00fcddeutsche Zeitung]] |location=Munich |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n* 2000: [[M\u00fcnchhausen Prize]]<ref name=\"Schlamp\">{{cite news |last=Schlamp |first=Hans-J\u00fcrgen |date=24 April 2020 |title=Der Rentenversprecher |url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/norbert-bluem-ist-tot-ein-nachruf-a-44b5f142-83f2-4646-9a2e-8254c9326b27 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |location=Hamburg |language=de |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n* 2001: [[Leipzig Human Rights Award]]<ref name=\"Schlamp\" />\n* 2005: [[Leopold Kunschak Prize]]<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date=11 March 2005 |title=Einladung zur Pressekonferenz mit BM a.D. Norbert Bl\u00fcm und Werner Fasslabend |url=https://www.ots.at/presseaussendung/OTS_20050309_OTS0130/einladung-zur-pressekonferenz-mit-bm-ad-norbert-bluem-und-werner-fasslabend |work=ots.at |location=Vienna |publisher=APA-OTS |language=de |agency=APA |access-date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{DNB portal|118722395}}\n* {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009024102/http://www.partner-erde.de/deutsch/gruendung-rahmen.html |date=9 October 2007 |title=Norbert Bl\u00fcm's article on the founding of the Scout Group \"Partner Erde\" in R\u00fcsselsheim ''(German)'' }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071115032636/http://xenutv.com/trust/leipzig-2001.htm The 2001 Leipzig Human Rights Award], video coverage of the event at ''[[Mark Bunker|Xenu TV]]'', 9 June 2001\n* [https://www.bundesarchiv.de/cocoon/barch/1121/z/z1960a/kap1_2/para2_124.html Kabinettsprotokolle Online \"Bl\u00fcm, Norbert\"] (in German) bundesarchiv.de\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blum, Norbert}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from R\u00fcsselsheim]]\n[[Category:Christian Democratic Union of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:People from the People's State of Hesse]]\n[[Category:Labor ministers (Germany)]]\n[[Category:Social Affairs ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for North Rhine-Westphalia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Bundestag for Rhineland-Palatinate]]\n[[Category:Senators of Berlin]]\n[[Category:University of Bonn alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Leopold-Kunschak-Prize]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses with Star and Sash of the Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life and education:wl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norbert_Bl%C3%BCm"}
